2 reactions"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ECytochrome P450 enzymes are primarily found in the \u003Cstrong\u003Esmooth endoplasmic reticulum\u003C/strong\u003E of liver and intestinal cells. They are involved in phase 1 reactions, which include oxidation, reduction, and hydrolysis, rather than phase 2 reactions. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhase 2 reactions require cytochrome P450 as an electron carrier\u003C/strong\u003E - Cytochrome P450 enzymes are involved in phase 1 reactions, not phase 2\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFamilies 1, 2, and 3 are responsible for the metabolism of a small number of drugs\u003C/strong\u003E - These families metabolise most clinically used drugs\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThere are cytochrome P450s for only a small number of foreign organic molecules\u003C/strong\u003E - Cytochrome P450 enzymes metabolise a wide variety of foreign organic molecules\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECytochrome P450 enzymes are primarily involved in phase 2 reactions\u003C/strong\u003E - They are primarily involved in phase 1 reactions\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Cytochrome P450 enzymes are primarily found in the smooth endoplasmic reticulum of liver cells.","Cytochrome P450 enzymes are involved in phase 1 reactions, which include oxidation, reduction, and hydrolysis.","Families 1, 2, and 3 of cytochrome P450 are responsible for the metabolism of most clinically used drugs.","Cytochrome P450 enzymes metabolise a wide variety of foreign organic molecules, not just a small number."],"references":["Gilbert-Barness, E., Barness, L. A., \u0026 Farrell, P. M. (Eds.). (2017). Metabolic diseases: foundations of clinical management, genetics, and pathology. IOS Press","Lanham-New, S. A., Macdonald, I. A., \u0026 Roche, H. M. (Eds.). (2011). Nutrition and metabolism. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Roche, H. M., Macdonald, I. A., Schols, A. M., \u0026 Lanham-New, S. A. (Eds.). (2024). Nutrition and metabolism. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Omiecinski CJ, Vanden Heuvel JP, Perdew GH, Peters JM. Xenobiotic metabolism, disposition, and regulation by receptors: from biochemical phenomenon to predictors of major toxicities. Toxicol Sci. 2011 Mar;120 Suppl 1(Suppl 1):S49-75. doi: 10.1093/toxsci/kfq338. Epub 2010 Nov 8. PMID: 21059794; PMCID: PMC3145385"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63163"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17979"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63163","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63163"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-07T21:02:00+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-08T00:07:06+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10693"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77650"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt